Introduction

These notes focus on inspecting multivariate relationships between variables and transforming data based on these inspections, including an introduction to using PCA and K-Means clustering for exploration and feature engineering.

This is where things start to get interesting! We want to test our predictions about the data and identify the features that are most likely to contribute to predictive modeling. Multivariate plots give us our first peek at the answers to these questions.

Multivariate plots also help us to identify additional data cleaning steps and ideas for feature engineering. It is never to late to loop back and add additional data cleaning steps as you discover problems in the data.

Motivating example

I will use Rs built-in diamonds dataset as an example throughout these notes. The dataset on diamond prices invites us to predict the target variable price as a function of different characteristics of the diamond, including weight (carat), quality (cut), color, clarity, dimensions (x, y, and z), depth, and relative width of the top to the widest point (table):

# Create binary version of price variable

Multivariable Inspect-Transform-Inspect workflow (ITI)

In comparison to single variable ITI, there are many possibilities for multivariable plotting, so it is important to approach this portion of the project with a clear vision of what you are looking for. Here is an overview of the workflow for multivariate relationships:

  1. Inspect each target ~ predictor relationship. Does the relationship align with your expectations? Is the feature likely to be useful for predictive modeling? Are transformations needed?
  2. Check for high-dimensionality
    • 2a. IF you have multiple continuous predictors, check their correlations by visualizing pairwise relationships and correlations. If strong multicollinearity is present, consider dropping variables or reducing dimensionality with PCA.
    • 2b. IF you have categorical predictor(s) with sparse levels (e.g., less than 20 examples of a given category), devise a way to combine rare categories into larger groups.
  3. Perform transformations based on the inspections above.
  4. Plot a final set of post-transformation target ~ predictor relationships before modeling.

In addition, you may end up making ad hoc inspections to follow up on interesting observations or questions raised by your exploration.

Bivariate plots

Previously, we inspected individual continuous variables with histograms and categorical variables with tables or barplots. Now we want to visually inspect the relationships between pairs of variables with two-way, or bivariate plots. These are the simplest types of multivariate plots.

Bivariate plots are defined by which type of variable, continuous or categorical, is on the x and y axes. The most common types of bivariate plots include:

  • Scatterplots: A pair of continous features are represented as points in 2D.
  • Boxplots: Each box shows the distribution of a continuous variable, multiple boxes represent different categories.
  • Grouped density plot: This is useful for showing how density plots (similar to histograms) for a continuous variable differ across two or three categories.
  • Side-by-side/Stacked barplots: Each bar represents counts or propoportions of a given category.

Examples of each plot is shown below. I log transform price and caret since they have right-skewed distributions (not shown here):

# Scatterplot
g1 <- diamonds %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=log(carat), y=log(price))) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.2) + 
  ggtitle('Scatterplot: Continuous x Continuous')

# Boxplot
g2 <- diamonds %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=cut, y=log(price), fill=cut)) +
  geom_boxplot() + 
  ggtitle('Boxplot: Continuous x Categorical') +
  theme(legend.position="bottom")

# Grouped density plot (similar to histograms)
g3 <- diamonds %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=depth, fill=factor(high_price))) +
  geom_density(alpha=0.5) +
  ggtitle('Grouped density plot: Binary x Continuous') +
  theme(legend.position="bottom")

# Barplot (proportions, stacked)
g4 <- diamonds %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=clarity, fill=cut)) +
  geom_bar(position = 'fill') + 
  ggtitle('Stacked barplot: Categorical x Categorical') + 
  ylab('Proportion of each cut') +
  theme(legend.position="bottom")
grid.arrange(g1, g2, g3, g4, ncol=2)

Be sure you understand how to read these plots. Take a few moments to describe what each of the plots above tells us about the diamonds dataset:

  1. How is price related to carat?
    • A: As expected, higher caret (weight) is positively associated with higher price.
  2. How is price relted to cut?
    • A: Surprisingly, it looks like Fair cuts have the highest prices and Ideal cuts have the lowest prices. I would expect the higher quality cuts to have a higher price.
  3. How is depth related to price?
    • A: Greater depth is slightly associated with higher prices (blue distribution).
  4. How is cut related to clarity?
    • A: As we move from left to right, the different clarity levels are increasingly associated with the Ideal cut (yellow).

These plot types cover many common situations, however there will come a point where they are not enough. Dont panic! R and ggplot are versatile and the community is incredibly helpful. Think about the plot you want to make and find the words the describe it. Chances are, someone has been in your situation before and a well-posed Google search will lead you to a solution.

Transformations

The insights gleaned from your bivariate plots can be roughly broken down into two categories:

  1. Insights about which predictor variables are useful for modeling
    • If a predictor has no relationship or a complex relationship with your target, it will be challenging to model, so consider dropping it from the analysis
  2. Insights about possible problems or challenges, including:
    • Outliers or missing/incorrect data
    • Non-linear relationships
    • Sparse categorical features
    • Multicollinear continuous features
    • Hidden groupings

If outliers or missing data appear in the multivariable inspection stage, treat them as before: Try to understand why they exist and decide whether to throw them away or replace them with reasonable values. The other problems receive a more in-depth treatment below.

Problem: Non-linear relationships

What is non-linearity: Non-linearity arises when the relationship between a continuous target and a continuous or ordinal predictor is not a straight line, but rather a curve of some type.

Why is non-linearity a problem: Linear models assume that the relationship between the target and predictors can be modeled with a straight line, and violating this assumption leads to poor model performance.

Visual examples: The following plots show examples of linearity (top) and non-linearity (bottom) for a continuous target variable plotted against a continuous predictor (left) and an ordinal predictor (right):

# Simulate data
set.seed(37)
n <- 100
x <- 10 + rnorm(n)
x_ordinal <- ntile(x, 6)
y <- x + rnorm(n, sd=0.1)
df <- data.frame(y = y, x = x, x_ordinal = factor(x_ordinal))

# Continuous vs continuous: linear
g1 <- df %>% ggplot(aes(x=x,y=y)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', se=TRUE) +
  ggtitle('Linear: continuous ~ continuous')

# Continuous vs ordinal: linear
g2 <- df %>% ggplot(aes(x=x_ordinal,y=y)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', se=TRUE, aes(group=1)) +
  ggtitle('Linear: continuous ~ ordinal')

# Continuous vs continuous: non-linear
g3 <- df %>% ggplot(aes(x=x,y=exp(y))) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', se=TRUE) +
  ggtitle('Non-linear: continuous ~ continuous')

# Continuous vs ordinal: non-linear
g4 <- df %>% mutate(y_t = ifelse(y > mean(y), y - 2*(y - mean(y)), y)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=x_ordinal,y=y_t)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', se=TRUE, aes(group=1)) +
  ggtitle('Non-linear: continuous ~ ordinal')

grid.arrange(g1, g2, g3, g4, ncol=2)

Solution: Power transforms or binning

There is no one-size fits all solution to fixing non-linearities.

With a continuous vs continuous relationship, the most common cause of non-linearity is one or more of the variables being skewed or otherwise non-normally distributed. Thus, you can fix these probems by transforming the individual variables to have a normal distribution. For example, the non-linearity above (bottom left plot) occurs because the target variable is right skewed and needs to be log transformed.

With a continuous vs ordinal relationship (bottom right plot), non-linearity can be solved by binning the ordinal variable into a reduced number of levels, e.g., into binary high and low levels. The downside of binning is that it throws away information by reducing a granular variable into a crude binary one, but if your distribution is highly non-linear, binning is your last ditch option for eliminating the problem.

Problem: Sparse categorical features

What are sparse categories: A sparse category is a level of a categorical variable that has very few examples in your data.

Why are sparse categories a problem: To understand why this is a problem, it helps to realize that nearly all ML and statistical models, including linear and logistic regression, convert categorical variables into a set of dummy variables under the hood. Dummy variables encode the presence/absence of each level of the category as binary variables. For instance, if you have a categorical variable called Animal with the 3 categories dog, cat, and cow, this would be converted into 3 dummy variables as follows:

set.seed(37)

# Create original categorical variable
df <- data.frame(Animal = sample(c('dog','cat','cow'), 10, replace=TRUE))

# Create dummy variables for each level of the categorical variable
df$dog_dummy <- ifelse(df$Animal == 'dog', 1, 0)
df$cat_dummy <- ifelse(df$Animal == 'cat', 1, 0)
df$cow_dummy <- ifelse(df$Animal == 'cow', 1, 0)

# View table
kable(df)
Animal dog_dummy cat_dummy cow_dummy
cat 0 1 0
dog 1 0 0
cat 0 1 0
cat 0 1 0
cow 0 0 1
cow 0 0 1
cat 0 1 0
cat 0 1 0
dog 1 0 0
dog 1 0 0

Notice that for every row where Animal = dog, the dog_dummy column has a 1, otherwise it has a 0. The same is true for cat_dummy and cow_dummy. When a categorical variable with k levels goes into a linear or logistic regression, it actually gets converted into k - 1 dummy variables, with one of the categories being considered the baseline that each other categories get compared to. The resulting model will have k - 1 regression coefficients, each estimating the effect of a single category relative to the baseline category.

It follows that categories with sparse data (e.g., fewer than 20 observations) cannot be modeled with confidence. Moreover, from the perspective of the model, categorical variables with many categories can add a lot of complexity to models. Unnecessary complexity contributes to overfitting, or producing an overly specific model that captures random noise in the data and will not generalize well to new datasets. Overfitting is bad for BOTH model interpretability and predictive performance, since it leads to parameters modeling random noise rather than generalizable patterns.

Solution: Grouping rules

Given the discussion above, it is a good idea to keep this complexity as minimal as possible: Include only categories that add meaningful information to the model and eliminate sparse categories that cannot be modeled with confidence. But how can we combine sparse categories? It depends on the situation. Here is a non-exhaustive list of possibilities:

  • Combine all categories with fewer than n data points into a rare_category group.
  • Apply domain knowledge to come up with a sensible grouping of the categories (e.g., grouping countries into geographic regions).
  • Define categories with respect to some independent variable (e.g., clustering countries based on population size and GDP).

The important thing is to recognize excessive or sparse categories and devise a sensible rule to reduce the dimensionality of your categorical variables. Once you have devised a rule, functions such as ifelse, case_when, and recode may be helpful for engineering the new categorical variable.

Problem: Multicollinear continuous features

What is multicollinearity: Multicollinearity is a technical term for having highly correlated continuous predictor variables. As a rule of thumb, predictor variables with correlations greater than 0.8 deserve concern.

Why multicollinearity matters: Both linear and logistic regression assume that predictor variable contribute independent information to model predictions. Multicollinearity violates this assumption by introducing highly correlated variables that contain redundant information (which is the opposite of independent information). Multicollinearity results in models that are impossible to interpret and make unreliable predictions, so it is critical to detect and remove it before doing predictive modeling.

Intuitive example: Imagine we are trying to predict how tall babies will grow based on the length of their feet at birth. The right and left foot may differ slightly, but both feet are expected to be equally predictive of growth. The models height ~ left foot and height ~ right foot may produce nearly identical results that show a positive relationship between foot length and height. However, the model height ~ left foot + right foot is likely to produce wildly different estimates of the relationship for each foot. Changing the input data slightly could cause the relationships for each foot to fluctuate wildly, even swinging in the opposite direction. This pathological model behavior arises because the model cannot easily differentiate the influence of each foot on the target variable, since the contribute essentially the same information.

Ultimately, there are two reasons to avoid multicollinearity, one related to interpretation and the other related to predictive performance:

  1. Interpretation problem: When you have highly correlated predictor variables, models have a hard time differentiating their effects on the target variable. It causes regression coefficients to be extremely unstable and sensitive to small changes to the data, rendering regression coefficients uninterpretable.
  2. Predictive accuracy problem: Since highly correlated features contain redundant information, the estimated regression coefficients are at risk of capturing random noise in the dataset, leading to a model that performs well within the training data but does not generalize well to new datasets (also known as overfitting).

Since we will be using linear or logistic regression in our projects, we need to check for multicollinearity and address it if it is a problem. To check for multicollinearity, my preferred approach is to use the pairs.panel function from the psych package. I like this function because you can see scatterplots, correlations, and histograms of the continuous variables all in a single plot. Thus, this one plot can satisfy all of your needs for single and multivariable EDA of continuous variables!

Lets check the correlations among the continuous variables in the diamonds dataset for multicollinearity. Note that I only include the continuous predictor variables in the input dataframe:

# load psych library (must install it first)
library('psych')

# Log transform skewed variables, remove outliers, and isolate continuous variables
diamonds_cont <- diamonds %>% 
  mutate(log_carat = log(carat), 
         log_price = log(price),
         table = ifelse(table > 80, median(table), table),
         x = ifelse(x < 3, median(x), x),
         y = ifelse(y > 10, median(y), y),
         z = ifelse(z > 6, median(z), z)
         ) %>%
  select(-carat, -price, -cut, -color, -clarity, -high_price)
  
# View pairs plot
pairs.panels(diamonds_cont, pch=".")

What we see is several very strong correlations: x, y, z, and log_carat are extremely tightly correlated (r > 0.97), indicating that we have extreme multicollinearity.

Note: If you have too many points (e.g., more than 100-200), the scatterplots in the pairs.panels plot may become overly crowded, making it difficult to see the underlying relationship. You can make the points very small by adding the argument pch=".".

You can also use the built in R functions cor and pairs to get the same information, but less neatly packaged

Now that we know there is multicollinearity, we can address it in one of three ways:

  1. Selectively dropping collinear variables. This is the simplest approach. Ideally, you should have some justification for how you choose which variable(s) to keep. Perhaps one of the variables leads to more accurate predictions, or perhaps one variable has less missing data or fewer outliers.
  2. Combining collinear variables in some way (e.g., averaging them). Imagine you have scores on 10 different tests from students in a course, so each test is a column in your data. Assuming all the test scores are on the same scale (e.g., 0-100%), you could create a new average test score variable for each student to replace the multiple columns of test scores.
  3. Perform dimension reduction with PCA. PCA creates new mathematical combinations of the original variables, ensuring that the new variables (or Principal Components, PCs) are uncorrelated and sorted in order of how much variation they explain in the original variables. A subset of the most important PCs can be retained in downstream analysis in place of the original variables. Since PCs are uncorrelated by definition, they cannot suffer from multicollinearity.

Since the first two approaches dont require any new code or concepts, lets focus on PCA.

Solution: PCA dimension reduction

If you need a refresher on the basics of PCA, review the section on PCA in Instructor notes 1. The basic idea is that PCA takes N continuous input features, scales and rotates them to produce N new uncorrelated features called PCs which explain decreasing amounts of variation in the data, and then discards the least important PCs while retaining the most informative PCs (this last step reduces the dimensionality of the data, which is why this is called a dimension reduction). Our focus here will be on deciding how many PCs to keep from PCA.

The most common heuristic for choosing the number of PCs is to use a skree plot. A skree plot shows how quickly the sum of squares explained by each PC declines with each subsequent PC, with importance being measured by the proportion of variance in the original data that is explained by each PC. What people typically look for is the point of diminishing returns, or the elbow of the curve, because this is the point at which adding more PCs is expected to have a diminishing benefit.

Lets perform PCA on our diamonds dataset:

# drop target variable, log_price
diamonds_pca <- diamonds_cont %>% select(-log_price)

# Fit PCA model (variable scaling occurs automatically)
pc_model <- diamonds_pca %>% prcomp

# View PC variables
head(pc_model$x) %>% kable
PC1 PC2 PC3 PC4 PC5 PC6
3.1112099 -2.169226 -0.5692077 0.0479350 0.0703376 -0.0974578
-2.7421936 -4.309881 -0.2744978 0.0709613 0.0346231 -0.1472827
-7.2178818 -5.773027 -1.7969661 0.1204037 0.0232245 -0.0863784
0.4515084 -2.311599 1.1426641 0.0261992 0.0526698 -0.0412395
0.6075276 -1.890011 1.9551075 0.0194400 0.0635142 -0.0645038
1.6070592 -2.373624 1.2720466 0.0335736 0.0780317 -0.0884682 
# Check correlations between PC variables
cor(pc_model$x) %>% kable
PC1 PC2 PC3 PC4 PC5 PC6
PC1 1 0 0 0 0 0
PC2 0 1 0 0 0 0
PC3 0 0 1 0 0 0
PC4 0 0 0 1 0 0
PC5 0 0 0 0 1 0

You can see that PCA took the original 6 continuous variables and transformed them into 6 new continuous variables, or PCs, but unlike the original variables, the PCs have correlations of 0.

Lets look at the relative importance of each new PC with a scree plot to help us decide how many PCs will be useful to keep for downstream analysis:

# Visualize scree plot
fviz_screeplot(pc_model, addlabels = TRUE, ylim = c(0, 100))

There is a massive drop off after the first 3 PCs (if you look at the line, it is the elbow of the line), indicating that additional PCs capture little additional variation in the original variables. In other words, most of the information in the original 6 features can be consolidated into just the first 3 PCs which account for over 99% of the original variance.

Sometimes the elbow point is not very obvious. When the visual method fails, another common way to select the number of PCs is to define a proportion of the original variance that you wish to retain, such as 80% or 90%, and then keep the smallest number of PCs required to account for that much variance. For example, if we set our threshold to be 80%, the first 2 PCs would be sufficient since together they explain ~82.6% of the variance.

Once you have made your selection, the reduced set of PCs can be used as input features for preditive modeling. Here is an example of fitting linear models using the original 6 variables and the 4 top PCs. We could then evaluate these models on a holdout sample to determine which one performs better on an independent dataset.

# Add PC variables to the original dataframe
diamonds_new <- cbind(diamonds_cont, pc_model$x)

# View new dataframe
diamonds_new %>% head %>% kable
depth table x y z log_carat log_price PC1 PC2 PC3 PC4 PC5 PC6

59.8 61 3.89 3.84 2.31 -1.560648 5.786897 -2.7421936 -4.309881 -0.2744978 0.0709613 0.0346231 -0.1472827
56.9 65 4.05 4.07 2.31 -1.469676 5.789960 -7.2178818 -5.773027 -1.7969661 0.1204037 0.0232245 -0.0863784
62.4 58 4.20 4.23 2.63 -1.237874 5.811141 0.4515084 -2.311599 1.1426641 0.0261992 0.0526698 -0.0412395

# Fit linear regression using original 6 variables
lm_raw <- lm(log_price ~ depth + table + log_carat + x + y + z, data=diamonds_new)

# Fit linear regression using first 4 PCs
lm_pca <- lm(log_price ~ PC1 + PC2 + PC3 + PC4, data=diamonds_new)

By using the 4 PCs in place of the original 6 variables, we are in fact throwing some information away. The hope is that the information we are throwing away is random noise. How can we be sure this is a good decision?

The only way to be really sure is to systematically compare the accuracy of predictions using each possible number of PCs, but we dont have the tools to do that yet. We will learn to evaluate and compare model performance in a future set of Instructor notes.

Problem: Hidden groupings in the data

What are hidden groupings: Often, you will suspect that there are hidden groups in your data based on a mixture of data exploration and domain knowledge.

Why hidden groupings matter: Identifying clusters can be exciting. It can even be the star of your project if the clusters add insight or serve as new features for modeling. Clusters can add interpretability to results from PCA as well, since PCA will sometimes reveal clusters when you plot PC1 vs PC2.

Example of hidden clusters: Lets look at an example where PCA reveals hidden clusters in the data. The iris dataset provides a classic example. This dataset contains 4 measurements of the petal length/width and sepal length/width for individual flowers from 3 different species:

# Check iris dataset
iris %>% summary

Now, we know that these clusters correspond to different flower species. To prove this, here is the exact same plot with the actual flower species indicated by the color of points. We can see that there are actually 3 clusters, but the setosa species is much more distinct than versicolor and virginica:

# Visualize data along PC1 and PC2
fviz_pca_ind(pc_iris, col.ind = iris$Species)

Imagine we didnt have knowledge of which species was which. It would be very valuable to have a method that can identify these hidden groups. Lets see how K-Means clustering can help us label these hidden groups. We can then use the new groupings for further EDA or even as features in predictive models.

Solution: K-Means Clustering

If you need a refresher on the basics of K-Means Clustering, review the section on K-Means in Instructor notes 1. The idea is that you feed a set of continuous variables into K-Means Clustering and the algorithm finds a pre-specified number of clusters in your data. You can think of clustering as creating as a new categorical variable for your dataset by assigning a cluster ID to each row of input data.

A very important point about K-Means clustering which we have not discussed yet is that it requires the input data to be relatively uncorrelated and standardized. Lets clarify what this means and why it matters:

  • Inputs should be uncorrelated: K-Means clustering works by finding the centroid or average position of each cluster in the multivariate space defined by your input variables. If you have highly correlated input variables that represent redundant information, this redundant information will have an outsized influence on the clustering results. Inputs should be standardized: Standardized variables have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1 (this is achieved by applying the z-score transformaton: y <- (y - mean(y))/sd(y)). This transformation is critical to ensure that variables with large scales do not have an outsized influence on the clustering results. For example, if I am clustering individuals based on how likely they are to be admitted to an elite university and I have data on their SAT scores (mean 1800, standard deviation 200) and their family income (mean 60000, standard deviation 20000), the income variable is on a much larger scale, so it will contribute more to the clustering results unless we standardize everything to have the same mean and standard deviation.

Note that PCA also requires inputs to be standardized, but we havent had to worry about it because the prcomp function performs the standardization automatically. For the kmeans function, we must use the scale function to apply the standardization prior to passing the data to the model. Note that we also have to specify the desired number of clusters to the kmeans function with the centers argument. To begin, we will look for 3 clusters since we know there should be 3 species:

# Drop species variable and standardize with 'scale' 
iris_scaled <- iris %>% select(-Species) %>% scale

# Apply k-means clustering with k=3
kmeans_iris <- iris_scaled %>% kmeans(centers=3)

# Visualize results (we have to provide both the clusters and original data)
fviz_cluster(kmeans_iris, iris %>% select(-Species)  %>% scale)

It looks like K-Means Clustering found 3 clusters, but are the correct? We know that the clusters should correspond to the Species variable. Lets see how well they correspond by creating a table that shows the relationship between the clusters from our K-Means model and the original Species variable that we are hoping identify. Note that we can access the cluster IDs with kmeans_iris$cluster:

# Do the clusters capture different flower species?
table(iris$Species, kmeans_iris$cluster)
##             
##               1  2  3
##   setosa     50  0  0
##   versicolor  0 11 39
##   virginica   0 36 14

This table shows that the 3 species are somewhat, but not perfectly captured by the clustering. Cluster 1 contains all setosa, cluster 2 contains mostly setosa with only a few versicolor, and cluster 3 is evenly split between versicolor and virginica. This shows us that the clustering is able to separate setosa out, but it is having a difficult time separating versicolor and virginica into clusters. This makes sense in light of our earlier plots which found that versicolor and virginica are very similar in their measurements, while setosa is more distinct.

Perhaps this means we should be using fewer than 3 clusters. Lets use a more systematic approach to choosing the number of clusters by making an elbow plot, which is exactly analogous to the scree plot we made for PCA:

# Plot explained variance vs number of clusters
fviz_nbclust(iris_scaled, kmeans, method='wss')

As with the scree plot, this shows us how much additional variance is explained by adding more clusters to K-Means. The optimal number of clusters is found by identifying the elbow of the plot, or the point at which adding more clusters does not improve the amount of explained variance by much. Here, the elbow could be 2 or 3, but adding the 3rd cluster contributes much less than the first 2.

Based on this investigation, I might decide to use only 2 clusters, since the 3rd cluster is not really able to find a meaningful separation between species. If we wish to use the 2 clusters in further analyses, we could add them to the original iris dataset as follows:

# Create 2 clusters features
iris$Clusters <- iris %>% select(-Species) %>% scale %>% kmeans(centers=2) %>% .$cluster %>% factor

# Check results
iris %>% summary
##   Sepal.Length    Sepal.Width     Petal.Length    Petal.Width

##  1st Qu.:5.100   1st Qu.:2.800   1st Qu.:1.600   1st Qu.:0.300  
##  Median :5.800   Median :3.000   Median :4.350   Median :1.300  
##  Mean   :5.843   Mean   :3.057   Mean   :3.758   Mean   :1.199  
##  3rd Qu.:6.400   3rd Qu.:3.300   3rd Qu.:5.100   3rd Qu.:1.800

This demonstrates how you can use K-Means to explore structure in your data and engineer new categorical features representing the cluster IDs.

Concluding remarks

Skillful exploration, data cleaning, and feature engineering is where analysts have the most potential to differentiate themselves. Have the patience to get to know your dataset and treat it with care. It will pay off in the long run!
